	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I just released the source code of a MMC1 clone, which I just finished testing on real hardware.<br />It is well structured and commented, to allow anyone curious to look at it.<br />Posted in this forum:<br /><!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=9&amp;t=10010">viewtopic.php?f=9&amp;t=10010</a><!-- l --><br /><br />MMC1 is not complex, as it has been said, but it requires a XC9572 (44 pin chip).<br /><br />A XC9536 is not enough. It carries 36 macrocells, and my implementation requires 46 macrocells.<br />Keep in mind that MMC1 is serially loaded, which requires internal serial-parallel conversion; a shift register and a simple finite-state machine.<br /><br />MMC2, 4 are not complex either, but require more pins, as they are loaded in parallel.<br />Anyway, so far I don't plan to work on these mappers, so I can't say if a XC9536 will suit them.<br /><br />The most popular SEGA Master System mapper does seem to fit, though.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


